I believe the manufacturer is Arizmendi.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson S&W Schofield 1st Mod .45 Schofield At Least VG+ Condition
postcontent: This is truly a very nice 1st model, rated at least VG+. Considering the low numbers of these first variants that were produced, and then an even lower number that actually survived in somewhat decent condition having undergone cavalry issue during the Indian Wars, and then the rigors of frontier use. Most of these were later sold off as surplus only to have their barrels cut down, undergo refinishing with many of their numbered parts intermingled with others, and then commercially sold to the frontier market; it is then truly remarkable to find one that is as decent as this one. All numbers match, including the grip panels. The grips have never been messed with and still display the faint outline of the inspector’s cartouche on the left panel. The wood has only very minimal shrink and loss around the toe areas. There are minimal handling marks on the wood and absolutely no evidence of repairs. It retains the original oil finish. All metal stampings and letterings are sharp and very legible. Some of the screws appear untouched, while some show some use, but nonetheless are all in very serviceable condition.

The famous Winchester Model 1912 pump shotgun was designed by Winchester's Thomas C. Johnson. Introduced in 20 gauge in 1912, 16 and 12 gauge guns followed in 1914. title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt Sistema 1911 1927
location: Manheim, Lititz, Lancaster, Southeastern, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent:
For sale is an Argentine Sistema Colt Model 1927 Chambered for .45 ACP or if in Argentina, 11.25mm. This particular handgun was made in 1957 and is in very nice rust free condition for being so aged. With exception to a new Colt recoil spring, Wilson Combat grip screw bushings and allen head grip screws, as well as Magpul grips, this gun has all it's original parts. The barrel, slide, and frame have matching serial numbers. When I bought this, I originally intended to make it a project gun. When I brought it home it was bare of any finish. I stripped it down, cleaned it, gave it a cold blue finish, oiled it, and then shot it. Believe it or not, it shot great considering it's age. And all shots stayed within the 10 ring of the target at 10 yards. I had a lot of project ideas for this gun, but have run out of funds for other projects and need to let this guy go. It's a great solid gun. If you know anything about these guns, they were built on Colt machinery by workers trained by Colt in Argentina. This gun is basically a South American Colt and for being almost 60 years old, has a fairly tight slide to frame fit. If you have any questions or would like more pictures including a picture of the target, please feel free to ask. $485 gets you the gun as pictured,  as well as 2 used in excellent condition Kimber 8 round stainless magazines. Price is firm.

Can meet at Trop Gun Shop in Elizabethtown for a $16 transfer (buyer pays), or I can ship to buyer's FFL at buyers expense.
